\section{Requirements}

%claude:
This book assumes a good knowledge of the {C programming
language}. If that is not the case I suggest you first read
\emph{The C Programming Language}~\cite{k-r} and possibly also
\emph{Advanced Programming in the Unix Environment}~\cite{unix-stevens}.

%claude:
Basic familiarity with HTTP and HTML is helpful but not required.
The \book{Network} provides the necessary background on TCP/IP
and \plan's [[/net]] filesystem.
%
The \book{Kernel} explains how the kernel exposes network devices
(including [[/net/tls]] for TLS) and how namespaces work, which is the
substrate on top of which [[webfs]] operates.
%
The \book{Libcore} covers the user-space C library: [[fork]],
[[exec]], [[pipe]], [[print]], [[dial]], and the~9P client library that
[[webfs]] uses to serve [[/mnt/web]].
%
The \book{Widgets} describes [[libpanel]], the widget toolkit mothra
uses to lay out its address bar, display area, status bar, and form
widgets.

%claude:
Note that this book is {not} an introduction to the web or to HTML. Readers wanting
a gentler walk through how a browser works from first principles can
read \emph{Web Browser Engineering}~\cite{browser-engineering} in
parallel with this book.

