\chapter{Overview}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:overview}

%claude:
Before showing the source code of [[mothra]], [[webfs]], and the
supporting tools in the following chapters, I first give an overview
in this chapter of the general principles of a web browser.
%
I also describe the interfaces that make up the \plan web stack
(the [[/mnt/web]], [[/mnt/webcookies]], and [[/net/tls]] file servers),
walk through a complete [[hello.html]] document, explain how the
code is organized across several directories, and give the background
necessary to understand the code I will show later.

\section{Web browser principles}

%claude:
%terminology:
The {\em World Wide Web} (or just {\em the web}) is a {\em distributed
hypertext system} built on top of the Internet. Tim Berners-Lee
proposed it at CERN in 1989 and wrote the first working
browser-plus-server the following year.
%
It rests on three technical pillars, each the subject of a dedicated
subsection below:
{\em URL}, a universal naming scheme that lets any client address
any resource on any server (Section~\ref{sec:principles-urls});
{\em HTTP}, a simple text request/response protocol to fetch those
resources (Section~\ref{sec:hget-d-example});
and {\em HTML}, a lightweight markup format for the documents
themselves (Section~\ref{sec:principles-html}).
%
The user-facing idea that binds the three together is {\em hypertext}:
documents linked to each other through user-clickable anchors
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-hypertext}).
%
Layered on top of the base protocol are a handful of mechanisms the
web grew over its first decade:
redirection (Section~\ref{sec:principles-redirects}),
transport-level security (Section~\ref{sec:principles-tls}),
authentication (Section~\ref{sec:principles-auth}),
content negotiation by MIME type (Section~\ref{sec:principles-mime}),
character-set handling (Section~\ref{sec:principles-charset}),
embedded resources such as images (Section~\ref{sec:principles-refs}),
session state through cookies (Section~\ref{sec:principles-cookies}),
and user input through forms (Section~\ref{sec:principles-forms}).

%claude:
A {\em web browser} is the client side of this system: the program a
user runs to navigate between documents. The following subsections
explain, in turn, each core concept a browser must address --- and,
where relevant, what [[mothra]] does with it and what it leaves out.
% how the \plan design composes
%small programs to do the job, and what [[mothra]] deliberately leaves out.

\subsection{A viewer for hypertext documents}
\label{sec:principles-hypertext}

%claude:
A web browser is, at its core, a viewer for a particular kind of
document: {\em hypertext}. What distinguishes hypertext from ordinary
text is the {\em hyperlink} (or just {\em link}): a piece of {\em marked-up} text whose {activation}
fetches and displays another document, potentially somewhere else on
the network.
%
Stripped of the modern layers (styling, scripting, interactivity),
a web browser is then three things glued together:
a {\em fetcher} (given a name, get the bytes),
a {\em parser} (given bytes, find the text and the links), and
a {\em renderer} (given text and links, show them on screen and let the user click).
%
[[mothra]] implements exactly these three and nothing more.

%claude:
%cs-history:
The web was not the first hypertext system; almost every idea in it
has an older precursor. Vannevar Bush sketched the {\em Memex} in
his 1945 essay {\em As We May Think}: a mechanical desk of microfilm
that a user would stitch together into ``trails'' of linked documents.
Ted Nelson coined the words {\em hypertext} and {\em hyperlink} in
1965 and spent decades pushing his Xanadu design.
Doug Engelbart built the first working hypertext system, NLS, and
demonstrated it live in 1968 in the now-famous {\em Mother of All
Demos}. Apple's HyperCard (1987) put linked ``cards'' on millions
of Macintosh desktops. On the Internet itself, the web had direct
contemporaries: Gopher (1991) served hierarchical menus of documents,
and WAIS (1991) served keyword-searchable collections.
%
What the web added was three things at once that none of the
precursors combined: a single global address space for all resources
(the URL), one simple text protocol to fetch them (HTTP), and a
document format that could embed images and links without requiring
a custom client per server (HTML). That combination was enough to
crowd out the alternatives by about 1994.

\subsection{The URL as universal name}
\label{sec:principles-urls}

%claude:
%terminology:
A {\em URL} (Uniform Resource Locator) is the universal name of a
{\em resource} on the web.
%
Its syntax has many components and has the shape
\texttt{scheme://host:port/path?query\#fragment}, where the {\em scheme}
(usually [[http]] or [[https]]) selects the protocol, the {\em host} and
{\em port} identify the server, the {\em path} identifies the resource within the
server, the {\em query} carries parameters, and the {\em fragment} names an
{\em anchor} inside the document.
\n miss the user@ part too

%claude:
A concrete URL with all components labelled:
%
\begin{verbatim}
        https :// en.wikipedia.org : 443 / wiki/Cat ? lang=en # refs
        ^^^^^    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^   ^^^   ^^^^^^^^   ^^^^^^^   ^^^^
        scheme   host                port  path       query     fragment
                 \____________________ ___________/
                                      v
                                    authority
\end{verbatim}
%
URLs are the input to nearly every browser operation: the {address
bar} accepts them, hyperlinks embed them, {bookmarks} record them.

%claude:
%terminology:
The [[:port]] part is usually elided. Each scheme has a {\em default
port}: [[http]] defaults to 80, [[https]] to 443, [[ftp]] to 21.
So \verb+http://example.com/+ and \verb+http://example.com:80/+
name the same resource, and a browser silently fills in the default
before dialing. An explicit port is only written when the server is
listening somewhere else---the canonical example being [[8080]],
which non-root users can bind without elevated privileges and which
most development HTTP servers therefore default to.

%claude:
%cs-history:
The leading [[www.]] (for World Wide Web) on so many older URLs is not part of the web
protocol---it is just a DNS {\em subdomain} convention from the
early 1990s. When a site ran several Internet services on the same
domain, administrators named each service's host separately:
\verb+ftp.example.com+, \verb+mail.example.com+,
\verb+gopher.example.com+, and---for the web server---
\verb+www.example.com+. Nothing forced it, but the convention stuck
and for years users typed [[www.]] almost reflexively. These days
most sites serve the same content at both \verb+example.com+ and
\verb+www.example.com+, typically with a 301 redirect
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-redirects}) from one to the other.

%claude:
URLs can be {\em absolute} (they specify the scheme and host) or
{\em relative} (they omit those and are resolved against the URL of
the current page). Resolving relative URLs is a more subtle operation
than it first appears---it involves dot-segment normalization, handling
of paths versus authorities, and careful distinction between the URL
of the document and the [[<base>]] declared inside it. 
%
I devote Chapter~\ref{chap:urls} entirely to URL parsing and resolution.

%yoann: maybe reference Network book and the host:port part are handled by IP and DNS and TCP/IP machinery (and dial() in the case of mothra? from libcore book?
%claude:
%cross-book:
A URL names a resource, but only the {\em path}, {\em query}, and
{\em fragment} are really the browser's concern. The {\em host} and
{\em port} are handed off to lower layers: the host is resolved to
an IP address by DNS, and a TCP connection is opened to that address
on the named port. Both DNS and TCP/IP are covered in the \book{Network}.

On \plan, reaching the host and port reduces to a single [[dial()]] call from the
C library (\book{Libcore}), which hides DNS resolution and connection
setup behind a file-server interface ([[/net/]]).
%
In our stack, [[hget]] and [[webfs]] are the ones that actually call
[[dial(netmkaddr(host, "tcp", port))]] (or go through
[<iotlsdial()>] for HTTPS); mothra itself never sees IP addresses,
because it delegates all fetching to [[webfs]] through
[[/mnt/web/$n$/ctl]].

\subsection{HTTP: Client/server over a text protocol}
\label{sec:hget-d-example}

%claude:
A browser fetches resources by speaking HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)~\furl{https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2616}, a
{\em request/response protocol} carried over TCP (or TLS over TCP, for HTTPS).
%plan9-is-cleaner:
HTTP is remarkable for being a {\em text protocol}: a request is literally
a few human-readable lines, as is a response.
%
You can see the whole thing by running:
%
\begin{verbatim}
% hget -d http://example.com/
4 -> GET / HTTP/1.0
Host: example.com
User-agent: Plan9/hget
Cache-Control: no-cache
Pragma: no-cache
4 ->
4 <- HTTP/1.1 200 OK
4 <- Date: ...
4 <- Content-Type: text/html
4 <- Connection: close
4 <- Server: cloudfare
...
<!doctype html><html>...</html>
\end{verbatim}
%
The server's response is a {\em status line} (\verb+HTTP/1.1 200 OK+),
a list of [[Name: value]]
{\em headers}, a blank line, and the {\em body}. No binary framing, no schemas.
%
This is one reason the web grew so fast: anybody could debug
an HTTP exchange with [[telnet]] and a keyboard. \plan's [[hget]],
which I describe in Chapter~\ref{chap:hget}, is not much more than
[[telnet]] plus URL parsing plus redirect handling.

%claude:
%terminology:
Those [[Name: value]] headers carry
everything that is not the resource itself. They come in two flavors.
%
{\em Request headers} (sent by the browser) advertise what the client
wants or can accept: [[Host:]] selects the virtual host on a shared
server, [[User-Agent:]] identifies the browser, [[Accept:]] lists
tolerated MIME types (Section~\ref{sec:principles-mime}),
[[Accept-Encoding:]] gossips about [[gzip]] support,
[[Cookie:]] echoes back session state
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-cookies}), and
[[Referer:]] names the page that contained the link.
%
{\em Response headers} (sent by the server) describe the resource
being returned: [[Content-Type:]] is the MIME type that tells the
browser whether to render, save, or dispatch to an external viewer
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-mime});
[[Content-Length:]] sizes the body;
[[Content-Encoding:]] flags compression and interacts with charset
handling (Section~\ref{sec:principles-charset});
[[Location:]] carries the target of a redirect
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-redirects});
[[Set-Cookie:]] hands a cookie to the browser
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-cookies});
[[Cache-Control:]] and [[Expires:]] control caching.
%
A few headers can appear on either side (for example [[Date:]],
[[Connection:]], [[Content-Type:]] when a request itself carries a
body, as in form [[POST]]s — Section~\ref{sec:principles-forms}).
%
The header block is open-ended: unknown headers are ignored, which
is how the protocol grew from a handful of fields in 1991 to dozens
today without ever breaking older clients.

\subsection{Redirects}
\label{sec:principles-redirects}

%claude:
%terminology:
A server can respond to a request not with the resource itself but
with a {\em redirect}: an HTTP status code in the [[3xx]] range
(typically [[301 Moved Permanently]] or [[302 Found]]) plus a
[[Location:]] header naming a different URL. The browser is expected
to fetch that URL and try again, possibly several times in a row.
%
Redirects are pervasive: they are
how sites switch from [[http]] to [[https]],
how URL shorteners work,
how login flows return to the original page after authentication.

%claude:
A redirect chain in time, for a fetch of \verb+http://bit.ly/abc+
that bounces twice before landing:
%
\begin{verbatim}
    browser                    bit.ly       example.com
    -------                    ------       -----------
    GET /abc HTTP/1.0    -->
                          <--   301 Moved Permanently
                                Location: http://example.com/foo
    GET /foo HTTP/1.0                  -->
                                        <-- 302 Found
                                            Location: /foo/index.html
    GET /foo/index.html                -->
                                        <-- 200 OK
                                            <body>...
\end{verbatim}
%
Each row is one HTTP exchange; arrows mark the direction. The browser
walks the chain in a tight loop, calling [<parseurl()>] on each
[[Location:]] (against the current URL as base, so relative redirects
work) and re-issuing the request.

%claude:
%terminology:
Because a misconfigured server can redirect a URL back to itself
(or two URLs to each other), every browser caps the number of hops
it will follow---usually 10 or so---and reports a {\em redirect loop}
error past that. The redirect-follow logic also has to interact with
cookies (a [[Set-Cookie:]] header from the redirecting response
must be honoured before the new fetch sends [[Cookie:]]) and with
authentication (credentials usually do {\em not} cross domains).
Both [[hget]] and [[webfs]] implement the redirect loop;
Chapter~\ref{chap:hget} is the simpler of the two.

\subsection{TLS and HTTPS}
\label{sec:principles-tls}

%claude:
%terminology:
{\em HTTPS} is HTTP wrapped in {\em TLS} (Transport Layer Security,
the modern successor of SSL). The bytes that travel on the wire are
encrypted; the bytes the HTTP code reads and writes above are
unchanged. This is the cleanest abstraction layering in the whole
web stack: a TLS-aware [[connect]] returns an encrypted file
descriptor, and from then on everything looks like plain HTTP.

%claude:
The TLS handshake authenticates the server (via an X.509 certificate
signed by a trusted Certificate Authority) and negotiates an
encryption cipher and session keys. The browser must verify the
certificate's chain of trust, check that the server name matches the
URL's host, and reject the connection on any failure. The handshake
also includes a {\em Server Name Indication} (SNI) field sent by the
client so virtual-hosted servers can pick the right certificate
before the encrypted channel is established.
%
%plan9-is-cleaner:
[[mothra]] inherits all of this from the \plan [[libsec]] library;
the integration point is one call to [[tlsClient()]] in [[webfs]]
(Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}) and another in [[hget]]
(Chapter~\ref{chap:hget}).

\subsection{HTTP authentication}
\label{sec:principles-auth}

%claude:
%terminology:
Some resources require {\em authentication}: the server responds
with [[401 Unauthorized]] and a [[WWW-Authenticate:]] header that
names a {\em scheme} (typically [[Basic]] or [[Digest]]) and a
{\em realm} (a string identifying the protected zone, e.g.\
\verb+"company intranet"+). The browser is expected to prompt the
user for credentials, encode them as the scheme requires, and retry
the request with an [[Authorization:]] header. 
%
\begin{verbatim}
    browser                              server
    -------                              ------
    GET /private HTTP/1.0          -->
                                    <--  401 Unauthorized
                                         WWW-Authenticate: Basic realm="x"
    [prompt user for user/passwd]
    GET /private HTTP/1.0
    Authorization: Basic dXNlcjpwYXNz   -->
                                    <--  200 OK
                                         <body>...
\end{verbatim}

Subsequent requests
to the same realm re-send the cached credentials automatically
so the user is not re-prompted.


%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
\plan handles credential prompting through [[factotum]] (see the
\book{Kernel}), which means [[mothra]] does not have its own login
dialog: it asks [[factotum]] for the [[user]]/[[passwd]] pair for
the host+realm; [[factotum]] either looks up an existing entry or
prompts the user via its own UI; the result comes back through a
small library call. The integration is described in
Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}.

\subsection{MIME types and content dispatch}
\label{sec:principles-mime}

%claude:
%terminology:
HTTP responses include a [[Content-Type:]] header that names the
kind of data in the body (see the [[hget -d]] trace
in Section~\ref{sec:hget-d-example}).
%
The naming scheme, borrowed from email, is
the {\em MIME type}: a [[type/subtype]] string like [[text/html]],
[[image/png]], [[application/pdf]], or [[application/json]]. 
%
The top-level [[type]] (text, image, application, audio, video, multipart,
\ldots) is one of a small fixed set; the [[subtype]] is the specific
format.

%claude:
%terminology:
The browser uses the MIME type to decide how to render the body:
[[text/html]] goes to the HTML parser, [[image/*]] to an image
decoder, [[text/plain]] to a plain-text view, anything unknown is
typically saved to a file or handed to a separate viewer. When the
server's [[Content-Type:]] is absent or wrong (which happens often
on the real web), the browser falls back to {\em content sniffing}:
peek at the first few bytes and guess.
%
I describe both the dispatch and the sniffing logic in
Chapter~\ref{chap:content-dispatch}.

\subsection{Character encodings}
\label{sec:principles-charset}

%claude:
%terminology:
The web browser receives bytes from the requested server, but
bytes are not text. To display the bytes of an HTML document the
browser must know which {\em character encoding} (or {\em charset})
was used to produce them: a mapping from byte sequences to characters.
%
The web inherited many encodings from the pre-Unicode era---ISO~8859-1
(Western Europe), Shift-JIS (Japan), Big5 (Taiwan), GB2312 (China),
KOI-8 (Russia)---and slowly converged on {\em UTF-8},
%, Windows-125x
the modern Unicode encoding that subsumes all of them.

%claude:
A browser detects which encoding to use from three sources, in
priority order:
%
\begin{verbatim}
       1. byte-order mark (BOM)         the first 2-3 bytes of the doc
                |  no BOM
                v
       2. charset= in Content-Type      from the HTTP response header
                |  no charset attr
                v
       3. <meta charset="...">          inside the HTML <head>
                |  no meta either
                v
       4. fall back to a default        (Latin-1 or sniff for UTF-8)
\end{verbatim}
%
The first source that fires wins; later sources are ignored.

%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
\plan is UTF-8 throughout, which means every non-UTF-8 page must be
converted before the renderer sees it. [[mothra]] does this by piping
incoming HTML through two helper programs, [[uhtml]] (sniffer +
dispatcher) and [[tcs]] (the actual converter), covered in
Chapter~\ref{chap:charset}.

\subsection{HTML as the document format}
\label{sec:principles-html}

%claude:
%terminology:
The {\em HyperText Markup Language} (HTML) is the document format
of the web. An HTML document is plain text with embedded {\em tags}
in angle brackets ([[<p>]], [[<a>]], [[<img>]], \ldots) that mark
up parts of the text with semantics: ``this is a paragraph'', ``this
is a link to that URL'', ``this is an image''. Most tags come in
opening/closing pairs ([[<p>]]\ldots[[</p>]]) that nest into a tree;
a few ``void'' tags ([[<img>]], [[<br>]], [[<hr>]]) stand alone.
%
Tags carry {\em attributes} as [[name=value]] pairs inside the
opening tag---the essential ones for a hypertext system being
[[href=]] on [[<a>]] (the link target) and [[src=]] on [[<img>]]
(the image URL). Section~\ref{sec:principles-refs} discusses how
the browser follows those references.

%claude:
A tiny but complete HTML document:
%
\begin{verbatim}
    <html>
    <head><title>Hello</title></head>
    <body>
      <h1>Welcome</h1>
      <p>This is a paragraph with a
         <a href="http://example.com/">link</a>
         and an <img src="logo.png" alt="logo">.</p>
    </body>
    </html>
\end{verbatim}
%
The tree is shallow: [[<html>]] contains [[<head>]] (metadata, here
just the window [[<title>]]) and [[<body>]] (visible content). Inside
the body, [[<h1>]] is a heading and [[<p>]] is a paragraph containing
mixed text, one [[<a>]] anchor with an [[href=]] pointing at another
URL, and one [[<img>]] with [[src=]] naming an image to fetch. The
[[alt=]] attribute on [[<img>]] supplies text shown in place of the
image if the fetch fails or the browser does not render images (as
when [[mothra]] is invoked with [[-k]]).
%
Section~\ref{sec:hello-html} walks through a slightly bigger example
end-to-end: what [[mothra]] prints, what [[webfs]] does, and how
[[getpix]] inlines the image.

%claude:
%cs-history:
HTML descends from SGML, IBM's heavy markup language of the 1970s,
stripped down by Tim Berners-Lee to a handful of tags usable by
non-experts. It was never formally standardized at version~1; the
first real spec was HTML~2.0 (RFC~1866, 1995), which already
introduced forms. HTML~3.2 (1997) added tables, HTML~4 (1999) added
more semantic tags, XHTML~1.0 (2000) tried to re-cast HTML as
strict XML (and lost), and HTML5 (2014) finally gave up on
strictness entirely and defined a lenient parsing algorithm
instead. Chapter~\ref{chap:html-parsing} covers what [[mothra]]
parses.

%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
Lenient parsing is a load-bearing feature of the web: real-world
HTML is full of unclosed tags, mismatched nesting, and pre-HTML5
quirks, and every browser---including [[mothra]]---has to recover
gracefully rather than reject the document. [[mothra]] accepts
HTML~4-style markup (no HTML5-specific constructs) and is
deliberately forgiving about everything else; I describe the
tokenizer and tag dispatcher in Chapter~\ref{chap:html-parsing}.

\subsection{Rendering text with structure}% (no layout engine required)}
\label{sec:principles-render}

%claude:
Once the HTML arrived, the browser has to turn it into something
the user can see.
%
%modern:
Modern browsers use a {\em box model}: every HTML element becomes a
rectangular box, boxes {nest} and {flow} according to CSS rules, and a
{\em layout engine} (thousands of lines of code) computes positions and
sizes. This is how a page with a three-column grid, a sticky header,
and a pop-up menu gets laid out.

%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
[[mothra]] does none of that. It treats an HTML document as a
{linear flow of text} with inline markup, much like a word processor:
the tokens come out of the parser and are word-wrapped into paragraphs,
with occasional images, form fields, or links embedded in the flow.
%
There is no box model, no column layout, no CSS. Most HTML~2 and
HTML~3.2 documents render perfectly well this way; modern pages
designed around grids and flex boxes render as reflowed text, which
is usually still readable if not pretty.

%claude:
This is the same simplification the text-mode browsers ([[lynx]],
[[links]], [[w3m]]) make. The lesson [[mothra]] teaches is that
a big portion of what a browser {\em does} can be done with a
flow-text view and nothing more---the box model is an optimization
for visually rich layouts, not a requirement for reading documents.

\subsection{Documents reference other resources}
\label{sec:principles-refs}

%claude:
%terminology:
A web page is not a single fetch. The HTML document is the
{\em main resource}, but it typically references other resources to
be fetched separately: inline images via [[<img>]], stylesheets via
[[<link rel=stylesheet>]], scripts via [[<script src=>]], fonts,
iframes, and so on. Each reference is a URL, each URL becomes its
own HTTP request, and the browser must walk the document while
fetching the {\em sub-resources} in parallel.

%claude:
%terminology:
Some sub-resources block rendering (CSS must be applied before the
first paint, blocking scripts run before the parser continues),
others don't (images, async scripts, fonts). Either way, sub-resources
arrive {\em asynchronously}, after the main document is already being
rendered, which means the layout has to absorb them late: an
[[<img>]] is initially rendered as a blank placeholder or alt-text,
and when the image bytes arrive (revealing the actual dimensions)
the surrounding text has to be re-laid-out. This re-layout triggered
by deferred information is what browser literature calls {\em reflow}.

%claude:
A trivial page with two images shows the parallel-fetch and reflow
pattern in time:
%
\begin{verbatim}
    time
     |  +------------------+
     |  | GET /page.html   |   <- main fetch
     |  +--------+---------+
     |           v
     |  parse... discover <img src="a.png">, <img src="b.png">
     |           |  fork in parallel
     |    +------+------+
     |    v             v
     |  GET a.png    GET b.png        <- subresource fetches in parallel
     |    |             |
     |    | (page already showing alt-text placeholders)
     |    v             v
     |  decode        decode
     |    |             |
     |    v             v
     |  reflow        reflow            <- each image arrival re-lays out
     v
\end{verbatim}
%
The reader sees text first, then images popping in one by one with
the surrounding text shifting each time.

%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
[[mothra]] only fetches the resources it understands: the main HTML
document and its inline [[<img>]] images.
%
Stylesheets and scripts are
ignored (since [[mothra]] does not implement CSS or JavaScript).
%
Even with that simplification, the parallel-fetch and async-reflow
machinery is still present: Chapter~\ref{chap:images} describes how
[[mothra]] uses [[getpix]] subprocesses to fetch and decode images
in parallel, with placeholders rendered first.

\subsection{Cookies and stateful sessions}
\label{sec:principles-cookies}

%claude:
%terminology:
HTTP itself is {\em stateless}: every request is independent, and the
server has no built-in way to know that two requests come from the
same user. That works for fetching documents, but not for logging in,
keeping a shopping cart, or remembering preferences---so the web
needed a way to attach {\em session state} to the otherwise-stateless
protocol. The answer, bolted on top of HTTP in 1994 by Netscape, was
{\em cookies}\footnote{%
The name was borrowed from the older Unix/X Window
term {\em magic cookie}: an opaque token a program hands out and
later expects back unchanged, as a way of recognizing traffic it
already saw (for instance, X11's [[MIT-MAGIC-COOKIE-1]] authentication).
An HTTP cookie plays exactly that role.}.

%claude:
%terminology:
A {\em cookie} is a small named string that a server hands to the
browser via a [[Set-Cookie:]] response header; the browser stores it
and echoes it back on every subsequent request to the same site
through a [[Cookie:]] request header.
%
Each cookie has
a {\em domain} and
a {\em path} (the scope: it is sent only for matching URLs),
an {\em expiry} time (or none, meaning the cookie disappears when the browser exits), and
an optional {\em secure} flag (send only over
HTTPS).
%
The combined set of cookies a browser holds is called a {\em jar}.

%claude:
The full round-trip for a login flow:
%
\begin{verbatim}
    browser                                    server
    -------                                    ------
    POST /login (user=alice&pass=...)    -->
                                          <--  302 Found
                                               Location: /home
                                               Set-Cookie: sess=abc; Path=/;
                                                           Domain=example.com;
                                                           Expires=...
    [add cookie to jar, scoped to example.com / path=/]
    GET /home HTTP/1.0
    Cookie: sess=abc                     -->
                                          <--  200 OK  (logged-in page)

    GET /messages HTTP/1.0
    Cookie: sess=abc                     -->         <- same cookie sent again
                                          <--  200 OK
\end{verbatim}
%
Note how the server's response combines two of the mechanisms from
the earlier subsections: a [[302 Found]] redirect
(Section~\ref{sec:principles-redirects}) to steer the browser to
[[/home]], and a [[Set-Cookie:]] header piggy-backing on the same
response to install the session. The browser follows the redirect
exactly as in any other case, except that from the next request
onward it attaches the [[Cookie:]] header.

The server stores no per-user state in the cookie itself; the
\verb+sess=abc+ string is just a key into the server's {\em session table}.
The cookie's job is to identify {which session} belongs to {which browser}.

%claude:
%modern:
Cookies are also the basis of most web tracking: third-party
cookies (set by an embedded resource on someone else's page) let
advertisers correlate visits across sites.
%
Modern browsers respond
with elaborate scoping rules and partitioning policies.
%
[[mothra]] implements only the original RFC~6265 model (one jar, scoped by
domain/path/secure), which I describe in Chapter~\ref{chap:webcookies}.
The cookie file server [[webcookies]] is also covered there, along
with the dual implementation it shares with [[webfs]].

\subsection{Forms turn a viewer in a client of remote applications}
\label{sec:principles-forms}

%claude:
%terminology:
HTML has {\em forms}: a small set of input widgets ([[<input>]],
[[<textarea>]], [[<select>]], [[<button>]]) wrapped in a [[<form>]]
tag, with an {action} URL and a {submit} method.
%
When the user clicks
the submit button, the field values are encoded into an HTTP request
and sent to the action URL---the browser becomes, briefly, an
interactive client of the web application rather than a passive
viewer of a document.

%claude:
%cs-history:
Forms were not in the original HTML of 1991--1992 (the informal ``HTML
1.0''); they were introduced in the [[HTML+]] drafts in 1993 and
formalized in HTML 2.0 (RFC~1866, 1995). The web was a
document-viewing system for almost two years before it became
interactive.
%
Once forms existed, the user could finally {\em send} data to the
server, not just retrieve it: pick options from a menu, type a
search query, fill in a credit-card number. Almost everything we
think of today as ``the web'' grew out of that single addition---
search engines (AltaVista 1995, Google 1998) are forms that submit
a query and render the results page; online shopping (Amazon 1995,
eBay 1995) is forms that submit an order; webmail (Hotmail 1996),
social networks, blog comment boxes, online banking---all of them
are forms underneath. The browser stopped being a viewer and became
a {\em client} of remote applications.

%claude:
%terminology:
The form's [[method]] attribute selects how the data is sent.
[[GET]] appends the encoded fields as a query string to the URL
(\verb+?name=value&...+), suitable for searches and idempotent
operations.
[[POST]] sends the encoded fields as the request body,
with the encoding selected by the [[enctype]] attribute:
[[application/x-www-form-urlencoded]] (the default, the same
\verb+name=value&...+ format) for most forms, or
[[multipart/form-data]] (each field as a separate MIME part) when
file uploads are involved.

%claude:
Why two methods, why not just GET? Putting the data in the URL has
real consequences: the URL is logged by every proxy and server it
passes through, it shows up in [[Referer]] headers and browser
history, it is bookmarkable and shareable, it is cached, and there
is a practical length limit (a few kilobytes in most stacks). It is
also {\em idempotent} by convention: hitting reload, going back, or
replaying a request from history must not change anything on the
server.
%
That is exactly what you want for a search query (\verb+?q=cats+
in the URL is a feature: the user can bookmark the results page),
but exactly what you do not want for placing an order, sending a
message, or uploading a file. POST exists for that second case:
data goes in the body (no length limit, not in URL or [[Referer]]
or history), the browser warns before resubmitting on reload, and
intermediaries treat the request as state-changing (uncached, not
retried). The split is half a transport detail and half a contract:
GET means ``read,'' POST means ``do.'' The two methods on the wire:

\begin{verbatim}
    GET form (e.g. <form action="/search" method=GET>)
    -------------------------------------------------
        GET /search?q=cats&lang=en HTTP/1.0
        Host: example.com
                                                   <- fields in URL query
        (no body)

    POST form (e.g. <form action="/order" method=POST>)
    ---------------------------------------------------
        POST /order HTTP/1.0
        Host: example.com
        Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
        Content-Length: 31
                                                   <- fields in body
        name=Alice&item=widget&qty=3

    POST form with file upload (enctype="multipart/form-data")
    ----------------------------------------------------------
        POST /upload HTTP/1.0
        Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=XYZ

        --XYZ
        Content-Disposition: form-data; name="caption"

        my photo
        --XYZ
        Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="cat.jpg"
        Content-Type: image/jpeg

        <binary jpeg bytes>
        --XYZ--
\end{verbatim}
%
I describe how [[mothra]] maps form widgets to [[libpanel]] widgets
and how it encodes submissions in Chapter~\ref{chap:forms}.

\section{[[mothra]] interfaces}

%trans:
I just described the general principles of a web browser.
%and illustrated some of those principles with examples from [[mothra]].
%
I will now focus exclusively on [[mothra]] and give more details
about its interfaces.

%toc:
[[mothra]] is first a program you run through the command line, with 
optional command-line arguments. 
%
Then, it takes over the window (or screen when run outside [[rio]])
and becomes a graphical application.
%
Finally, it internally spawns new processes to interact with file servers. 
%
Thus, [[mothra]] has three different interfaces, which I will describe 
in the following sections.


\subsection{[[mothra]] command-line interface}

%claude:
The [[mothra]] command accepts a URL and a handful of flags:

\begin{verbatim}
    usage: mothra [-dvak] [-m mtpt] [url]
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
The [[-d]] flag enables debug tracing (each fetched URL is logged,
and images piped through [[resize]] are saved to [[/tmp/mothra-*.bit]]
for inspection).
%
The [[-m]] flag overrides the mount point for [[webfs]] (default
[[/mnt/web]]), useful for testing.
%
The [[-a]] flag starts mothra with the alternate ``ask'' panel
visible rather than the document panel, so the user types a URL
before any fetch happens.
%
The [[-v]] flag turns on verbose mode: HTML parsing errors are
written to file descriptor~2 instead of being silently swallowed.
%
The [[-k]] flag tells mothra to skip inline images (same as toggling
``kill images'' from the menu); useful over slow links.
%
If no URL argument is given, mothra falls back to the [[$url]]
environment variable; if that is also empty, it comes up with no
initial page and waits for the user to enter one.

\subsection{[[mothra]] graphical user interface}

%trans:
The most important interface of [[mothra]] is of course its
graphical user interface.
%
Figure~\ref{fig:mothra-gui} illustrates the main elements of [[rio]]'s GUI.

\begin{figure}\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=10cm]{pics/mothra-gui}
\end{center}
\caption{Graphical user interface of [[mothra]] after a right-click.}
\label{fig:mothra-gui}
\end{figure}

%yoann: describe main UI elements of mothra
%claude:
The window is divided into four stacked panels, top to bottom:
a one-line {\em status} area on the left paired with a {\em ``Go:''}
URL entry on the right (where the user types a URL or
[[/]]-search query); a scrollable {\em history list} of recently
visited pages; a {\em ``Url:''} label that displays the URL of the
page currently shown (and of any link the mouse hovers over); and
the main {\em text view} that holds the rendered document, with a
vertical scrollbar on the left and---when long lines are not wrapped
---a horizontal scrollbar on top.
%
Right-clicking anywhere pops up the {\em button-3 menu} shown in
the figure, with entries [[alt display]], [[moth mode]], [[snarf]],
[[paste]], [[plumb]], [[search]], [[save hit]], [[hit list]], and
[[exit]]. Left-clicking a link follows it; middle-clicking a link
loads it in the alternate display ([[alt]]).

%yoann: explain alt display and moth mode

\subsection{The \plan web stack interfaces ([[/mnt/web/]], [[/mnt/webcookies/]], \ldots)}

%claude:
\plan's design shows up not through a browser library, but through a
small set of {filesystem interfaces} that cooperating programs read
and write. The ones relevant to the browser are listed below; each
will get a full chapter later.

\subsubsection{[[/mnt/web]] ([[webfs]])}

%claude:
[[/mnt/web]] is the file tree served by [[webfs]]. It turns HTTP
(and HTTPS, and FTP) into filesystem I/O. A program that wants to
fetch a URL opens [[/mnt/web/clone]] (allocating a new connection),
writes the URL to the connection's [[ctl]] file, and reads the
resulting body, headers, and metadata from companion files like
[[body]], [[headers]], [[contenttype]], [[redirect]], and so on.
%
No program on \plan links [[libcurl]]. They all use [[/mnt/web]].

\subsubsection{[[/mnt/webcookies]]}

%claude:
[[/mnt/webcookies]] is a second file tree served by the
[[webcookies]] program. It persists cookies across [[webfs]]
restarts and across browsers.
%
A subtle point, covered in Chapter~\ref{chap:webcookies}, is that
[[webfs]] {also} has its own in-memory cookie store
(in [[webfs/cookies.c]]). Why both? Because [[webfs]] typically runs
per-window and its in-memory cookies die with it; [[webcookies]]
runs once per user session and survives.

\subsubsection{[[/net/tls]] and HTTPS}

%claude:
HTTPS (HTTP over TLS) is not implemented in [[webfs]] either. 
%
It is implemented by the \plan kernel as a device driver: [[/net/tls]] is
a file server served by [[devtls.c]] (see the \book{Kernel}). 
%
To send TLS records, [[webfs]] opens [[/net/tls/clone]], negotiates a
session via [[libsec]], and then writes plaintext: the kernel does
the encryption. This splits the browser's HTTPS story cleanly between
a small [[libsec]] client (thousands of LOC, in user space, replaceable)
and a simple I/O loop on plaintext files (unchanged since the 1990s).

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram illustrating all the actors, and maybe sequence diagram and see data exchanged (sometimes clear, sometimes encrypted)
%claude:
The four actors and the data that flows between them are sketched
below. Solid arrows carry plaintext (9P file I/O or unencrypted HTTP);
the dashed arrows are the only encrypted hop, between the kernel's
[[/net/tls]] device and the remote server.

\begin{verbatim}
   user space                              | kernel
                                           |
   +--------+   /mnt/web/$n$/{ctl,body}    |
   | mothra |<------------------------+    |
   +--------+                         |    |
        ^                             v    |    /net/tcp
        |    /mnt/webcookies      +-------+|   +--------+
        +-------------------+     | webfs ||-->| devip  |---> server
                            v     +-------+|   +--------+        ^
                       +-------------+ ^   |       (HTTP)        |
                       | webcookies  | |   |    /net/tls         |
                       +-------------+ +---|-->+--------+        |
                                           |   | devtls |~ ~ ~ ~ +
                                           |   +--------+   (HTTPS)
                                           |
   <--- 9P plaintext ---> | <- TCP plain -> | <~ TLS encrypted ~>
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
A few things to notice. (1) [[mothra]] never speaks HTTP and never
opens a network socket: it only reads and writes files under
[[/mnt/web]]. (2) [[webfs]] is the only program that ever sees
plaintext HTTP headers and bodies---it builds requests, parses
responses, follows redirects, and serves the result back through
[[/mnt/web]]. (3) The TLS boundary lives in the kernel
([[devtls.c]]): [[webfs]] hands [[/net/tls]] plaintext records and
the kernel encrypts them. So bytes are encrypted only on the wire,
between the [[/net/tls]] driver and the remote server; everywhere
inside the local machine they travel in the clear. (4) [[webcookies]]
is consulted on each request and updated on each response, but it
never talks to the network---it is a pure key/value file server.


\section{[[hello.html]]}
\label{sec:hello-html}

%claude:
The principles above are abstract; the rest of the chapter (and
much of the book) leans on a single small example to make them
concrete. Call it [[hello.html]]:

\begin{verbatim}
    <html>
      <head>
        <title>Hello, Principia</title>
      </head>
      <body>
        <h1>Hello, web!</h1>
        <p>This is a <b>tiny</b> document with a
           <a href="http://example.com/">link</a>
           and an image: <img src="logo.png">.
        </p>
      </body>
    </html>
\end{verbatim}

Now in a terminal run:
\begin{verbatim}
    % mothra file:hello.html
\end{verbatim}


%claude:
Figure~\ref{fig:mothra-hello-html} shows [[hello.html]]
rendered by mothra: a heading in bold type,
a paragraph of wrapped text with {\em tiny} shown in bold,
[[link]] shown as an underlined clickable anchor, and [[logo.png]]
fetched by [[getpix]] and inlined as a bitmap (the green [[9]] with brackets around).
Follow the [[link]] and mothra opens a new connection through
[[/mnt/web]], fetches [[http://example.com/]], parses the returned
HTML, and paints it in the same window.

\begin{figure}\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=12cm]{pics/mothra-hello-html}
\end{center}
\caption{The [[mothra]] rendering of [[hello.html]]}
\label{fig:mothra-hello-html}
\end{figure}


%claude:
Every detail in the preceding paragraph---the wrapping of text, the
discovery of the image URL, the spawning of [[getpix]], the
[[/mnt/web]] interaction---will be
%the back/forward history
explained in a separate chapter. The skeleton of the whole story
is in Figure~\ref{fig:arch}, further below.

%yoann: maybe explain file: is also a URL (but why missing // ?)
%claude:
%terminology:
The \verb+file:hello.html+ above is a real URL---[[file]] is a URL
scheme just like [[http]] or [[ftp]] (RFC~8089 spells it out). What
looks odd is the missing [[//]]. In the generic URL syntax of
RFC~3986, the [[//]] introduces the {\em authority} component
\verb+user@host:port+: it is what tells the parser ``what follows is
a host, not just a path.'' [[http://]], [[ftp://]], [[ssh://]] all
have an authority because they name a remote endpoint. Schemes
without an authority---[[mailto:alice@x.com]], [[tel:+15551234]],
[[urn:isbn:...]], [[data:text/plain,hi]], [[javascript:alert(1)]]
---write no [[//]] at all.
%
[[file:]] sits between the two: the formally correct form is
\verb+file:///path+ (the [[//]] introduces an empty
authority---``host = this machine''), but most tools, including
mothra, accept the lazy short forms \verb+file:/path+ and
\verb+file:hello.html+. mothra's [[fileget()]] in [[mothra/url.c]]
simply strips the [[file:]] prefix and opens the rest as a \plan
path, no \verb+/mnt/web+ round-trip needed.

%claude:
Once the bytes of [[hello.html]] are in hand---whether they came
from a [[file:]] URL or from [[/mnt/web]]---they are fed to mothra's
HTML parser, which produces the intermediate representation that
the rest of the browser works from. That representation is
deliberately minimal: a flat singly-linked list of % [[Rtext]]
{\em nodes}, one per text run, each carrying its own formatting
state and optional side-data. For [[hello.html]] above the list
looks like this:

\begin{verbatim}
    text                font   size      action               flags
    -------------------------------------------------------------
    "Hello, web!"       BOLD   ENORMOUS  -                    -
    "This is a "        ROMAN  NORMAL    -                    -
    "tiny"              BOLD   NORMAL    -                    -
    " document with a " ROMAN  NORMAL    -                    -
    "link"              ROMAN  NORMAL    {link="http://...",  PL_HOT
                                          name=nil, image=nil}
    " and an image: "   ROMAN  NORMAL    -                    -
    "[logo.png]"        ROMAN  NORMAL    {image="logo.png",   -
                                          link=nil}
    "."                 ROMAN  NORMAL    -                    -
\end{verbatim}
%
That is the entire intermediate representation. There is no DOM tree,
no element nodes, no parent/child pointers---just a singly-linked
list of text runs with per-run formatting and optional side-data. The
layout engine in [[libpanel]] then walks this list to produce the
on-screen pixels.


