\subsection{Composition through pipes and file servers}



%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
The most distinctive \plan contribution to the browser design is
the use of {file servers} and {pipes} where other systems use
libraries and frameworks.
%
Instead of linking a library like [[libcurl]] to speak HTTP, mothra
opens files under [[/mnt/web]]; the kernel routes those opens to the
[[webfs]] file server, which does the actual HTTP work.
%
Instead of linking a charset library like [[iconv]], mothra pipes
its input through [[uhtml]] (a 200-line program), which in turn
pipes through [[tcs]] (the \plan\ [[iconv]] equivalent).
%
Instead of forking a decoder into the browser process, mothra
spawns a separate [[getpix]] helper to fetch and decode images.

%\subsubsection{Pipelines: [[fetch | uhtml | render]]}

%claude:
%Mothra does not parse charsets, and its HTML parser assumes UTF-8.
%Many pages on the web are served in other encodings---Shift-JIS,
%GB2312, ISO-8859-1---and mothra deals with this through a {pipeline}:
%the fetched bytes are piped through [[uhtml]], a tiny program
%that sniffs the declared charset and, if needed, shells out to [[tcs]]
%to transcode to UTF-8. Only then do the bytes reach mothra's parser.
%%
%Chapter~\ref{chap:charset} shows the pipeline in detail.



%claude:
The same browser concerns get factored differently in other systems
as shown roughly in Table~\ref{tab:concern-split}.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
{\bf Concern}   & {\bf \plan / mothra}            & {\bf Linux GUI browser}  & {\bf Modern Chrome} \\
\midrule
HTTP            & \verb+/mnt/web+ file server     & libcurl in-process       & network process (sandboxed) \\
TLS             & \verb+/net/tls+ kernel device   & OpenSSL in-process       & BoringSSL in network process \\
Cookies         & \verb+/mnt/webcookies+          & SQLite file in-process   & SQLite in network process \\
Charset         & exec \verb+uhtml | tcs+         & libicu in-process        & ICU in renderer process \\
Image decode    & exec \verb+jpg/png/gif+         & libjpeg/libpng linked    & decoder process per-tab \\
Layout          & in-process (libpanel)           & in-process               & renderer process per-site \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Where each browser concern lives. \plan splits along
file-server boundaries; modern Chrome splits along process/sandbox
boundaries; classic Linux/Unix browsers do most things in-process
through linked libraries.}
\label{tab:concern-split}
\end{table}

%claude:
Two things to notice. First, modern Chrome and \plan happen to
{both} split the browser into multiple processes---but for different
reasons: Chrome does it for sandboxing (a compromise in one renderer
should not give the attacker the cookie jar), \plan does it for
sharing and replaceability (any program can mount \verb+/mnt/web+
and any user can swap out [[webfs]]). Second, the classic
Linux/Unix browser is the odd one out: it links everything together
because that is the path of least resistance when libraries are the
unit of composition.

%claude:
The benefit is twofold.
First, each piece can be replaced independently: 9front updated
[[libsec]] to support modern TLS cipher suites, and [[mothra]] gained
modern HTTPS with no code change whatsoever. Second, each piece is
reusable: [[hget]] and [[mothra]] share the same [[webfs]]; any
program that wants to read a URL can [[open]]\,[[/mnt/web/clone]];
charset conversion is available system-wide through [[tcs]].
%
Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs} explores this pattern in depth.



\subsection{Trace of a web request: [[mothra http://example.com]]}

%claude:
The traversal of the stack for a single page load is:

\begin{enumerate}

\item Mothra's [[main()]] calls [<geturl()>], which in turn calls
[<selurl()>] and [<seturl()>] (in [[mothra/mothra.c]]) to wrap
[[http://example.com]] in a [[Url]] object. The heavy parsing is
deferred: mothra keeps the URL almost verbatim and lets [[webfs]]
canonicalize it later (Chapter~\ref{chap:urls}).

\item Mothra opens [[/mnt/web/clone]]. The kernel routes the open
to [[webfs]], which allocates a new [[Client]] structure and returns
a connection number (Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}).

\item Mothra writes the URL to [[/mnt/web/$n$/ctl]]. Webfs parses
it with its full RFC 3986 parser ([[webfs/url.c]]), opens
[[/net/tcp/clone]] (or [[/net/tls/clone]] for HTTPS), and sends
the HTTP request (Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}).

\item Mothra opens [[/mnt/web/$n$/contenttype]] and reads the MIME
type. It uses [[snoop.c]] to dispatch (Chapter~\ref{chap:content-dispatch}).

\item Mothra opens [[/mnt/web/$n$/body]] and reads the bytes through
a pipe to [[uhtml]], which reads them back, sniffs the charset, and
pipes through [[tcs]] if needed (Chapter~\ref{chap:charset}).

\item The UTF-8 bytes reach mothra's [[rdhtml.c]], which tokenizes
the HTML, dispatches on tags, and builds a flat list of [[Item]]s
(Chapter~\ref{chap:html-parsing}).

\item The [[Item]] list is walked by the layout code, which word-wraps
it into text runs and emits libpanel draw calls
(Chapter~\ref{chap:layout} and Chapter~\ref{chap:tag-rendering}).

\item When an [[<img>]] tag is encountered, mothra [[fork]]s a
[[getpix]] subprocess and passes it a handle on the new
[[/mnt/web/$n$/body]]. [[getpix]] decodes the image (possibly piping
through [[resize]] if it is too large) and writes a bitmap that
mothra reads back and blits onto the panel
(Chapter~\ref{chap:images}).

\item The user clicks a link. Libpanel calls the anchor handler,
which extracts the target URL, resolves it against the base, and
goes back to step~2.

\end{enumerate}

%claude:
The same trace as a sequence diagram, with time flowing top to bottom
and each actor in its own column:

\begin{verbatim}
   user    mothra      webfs       /net/tcp     server     getpix    uhtml/tcs
   ----    ------      -----       --------     ------     ------    ---------
   click ->
           open clone --->
                       <--- conn n=7
           write ctl  --->
                       open ----------------> 80
                       write GET, Host, ...
                                    ----send---> [server thinks]
                                    <---recv---  HTTP/1.0 200, Content-Type: ...
                                                 <body>...
           read contenttype ->
                       <--- "text/html"
           open body  --->
                                                 \____ pipe ____/
                                                                  ---->  uhtml
                                                                         + tcs
                                                            UTF-8  <----
           parse...
           emit Rtext list                 (page rendering starts)
           see <img src=foo>
           fork getpix                              \------>  getpix
                                                              open /mnt/web/clone'
                                                              ...fetches foo...
                                                              decode bitmap
           <------ bitmap ---------------------------/
           reflow & redraw                           (image pops in)
\end{verbatim}

The reader can match each row of the diagram to one numbered step
above. Worth noticing: the only programs mothra ever directly opens
are \verb+/mnt/web/*+ files; everything below (TCP, TLS, charset
conversion, image decode) is reached transitively through file
servers and exec'd subprocesses, never through library calls inside
the mothra address space.

\section{Mothra for the pre-CSS, pre-JS web}

%claude:
%modern:
[[mothra]] is a browser for the {pre-CSS, pre-JavaScript} web.
It handles HTML tags (paragraphs, headings, lists, anchors, images,
forms, tables), follows links, submits forms, stores cookies, and
speaks HTTPS. It does not parse CSS. It does not run JavaScript.
It does not lay out pages as a box model. It does not handle
cross-origin policies, web sockets, service workers, WebAssembly, or
any of the many features modern browsers accreted since about~2005.

%claude:
%why-study:
Why study it, then?
Because the pre-CSS, pre-JS web {\em is} the substrate the modern web
is built on top of. HTTP has not fundamentally changed since~1996. HTML
tags still mean what HTML~3.2 said they meant. TCP, TLS, URLs, MIME,
cookies, forms: all of that is in [[mothra]], in about 4400 lines of
C you can read in a weekend. Understanding [[mothra]] gives you a
correct mental model for the bottom 90\%{} of what any browser does,
with none of the distractions of the top 10\%.

\section{Book structure}

%claude:
The book is organized in three parts, preceded by a short preface of
setup chapters and followed by a conclusion and the usual appendices.

%claude:
The {preface} (Chapters \ref{chap:intro}--\ref{chap:mothra-main})
contains this chapter, the core data structures used throughout the
code, and a walkthrough of mothra's [[main()]] and top-level event
loop. Reading [[main()]] early gives you the skeleton on which every
later chapter hangs.

%claude:
Part~I, {\em Retrieving the Page}, covers everything that happens before
mothra has any bytes to render: URL parsing
(Chapter~\ref{chap:urls}), the warmup HTTP client [[hget]]
(Chapter~\ref{chap:hget}), the [[webfs]] file server
(Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}), the [[webcookies]] companion
(Chapter~\ref{chap:webcookies}), the retrieval state machine inside
mothra (Chapter~\ref{chap:retrieval}), and the charset pipeline
(Chapter~\ref{chap:charset}). By the end of Part~I, clean UTF-8 bytes
are queued up for the parser.

%claude:
Part~II, {\em Rendering the Page}, picks up the bytes and turns them
into pixels: HTML parsing (Chapter~\ref{chap:html-parsing}),
MIME-based content dispatch (Chapter~\ref{chap:content-dispatch}),
the layout engine (Chapter~\ref{chap:layout}), the per-tag rendering
rules (Chapter~\ref{chap:tag-rendering}), tables
(Chapter~\ref{chap:tables}), images (Chapter~\ref{chap:images}), and
forms (Chapter~\ref{chap:forms}). By the end of Part~II, the page is
on screen and the user can interact with it.

%claude:
Part~III, {\em Beyond the Basics}, covers navigation and history
(Chapter~\ref{chap:navigation}), event handling and integration with
the rest of \plan (Chapter~\ref{chap:events}), developer tools
(Chapter~\ref{chap:devtools}), and advanced topics like proxies,
gzip, and FTP (Chapter~\ref{chap:advanced}).

%claude:
The {conclusion} (Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion}) summarizes what has
been covered, highlights the design patterns that recur across the
stack, and compares mothra with [[abaco]] and with modern browsers.
%
The {appendices} cover cross-cutting concerns---debugging, 
%profiling,
error management, and shared utilities.

%###############################################################################

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Core Data Structures}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:core-ds}

%claude:
In this chapter I introduce the data structures that the rest of the book
revolves around. They split cleanly along the boundary between the two
processes that together make up the browser: [[webfs]] owns
the network-facing types ([<Url>], [<Client>], [<Cookie>], [<Jar>], [<Ibuf>])
and [[mothra]] owns the rendering types ([<Tag>], [<Action>], [<Pair>],
[<Entity>], [<Www>]). The 9P file interface at [[/mnt/web]] is the only
thing connecting them; no shared header, no linked library.

%claude:
The relationships between the main types fit on one diagram:

\begin{verbatim}
    webfs side                          mothra side
    ----------                          -----------
    Client                              Www
      url ----> Url                       url ----> Url
      ctl                                 text ----> Rtext list
      creq                                pix
      io   ----> Ioproc                   form
      aux                                 (title, yoffs, ...)

    Jar                                 Rtext (libpanel)
      c    ----> Cookie[]                 (one node per text run,
      qid                                  links to Action for <a>/<img>)
      file
                                        Action
                                          link, image, field, ...
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
A web request becomes a [[Client]] inside [[webfs]] and a [[Www]]
inside [[mothra]]. Both keep their own copy of the parsed [[Url]] (each
side has its own [[url.c]] implementation, since serializing parsed URLs
across the file-system boundary would be silly). Cookies stay entirely on
the [[webfs]] side; mothra never sees them. The HTML parse tree never
crosses the boundary either: mothra reads the body bytes from
\verb+/mnt/web/N/body+, parses them locally into a flat list of
[[Rtext]] nodes (with [[Action]] side-data), and hands that to
[[libpanel]] for layout.

%claude:
A note on naming. Several types have the same C name in both programs but
different definitions: [[webfs]]'s \verb+struct Url+ carries a small
vtable for scheme-specific I/O ([[open]], [[read]], [[close]]) used inside
the file server, while \verb+mothra+'s \verb+struct Url+ is just the parsed
fields it needs to display, plus a couple of book-keeping flags. I tag the
chunks \verb+(webfs)+ and \verb+(mothra)+ to disambiguate.

\section{[[webfs]] URLs}

\subsection{[[Url]]}

%claude:
A [[Url]] in [[webfs]] is two things in one struct: the parsed components
of the URL (\verb+scheme+, \verb+host+, \verb+path+, \verb+query+,
\verb+fragment+, plus userinfo for FTP), and a tiny per-scheme vtable
([[open]], [[read]], [[close]]) so the request loop in
\verb+client.c+ can dispatch to the right backend without knowing anything
about HTTP, FTP, or \verb+file://+.

<<struct [[Url]](webfs)>>=
struct Url
{
    // ref_own<string>, the full URL string
    char*       url;

    // the scheme://[user[:password]@]host[:port]/path[?query][#fragment] components
    char*       scheme;
    char*       user;
    char*       passwd;
    char*       host;
    char*       port;
    char*       path;
    char*       query;
    char*       fragment;

    // enum<USCheme>
    int         ischeme;
    <<[[Url]](webfs) per-scheme methods>>
    union {
        <<[[Url]](webfs) union members>>
    };

    <<[[Url]](webfs) other fields>>
};
@

<<enum [[UScheme]]>>=
/*
 * If ischeme is USunknown, then the given URL is a relative
 * URL which references the "current document" in the context of the base.
 * If this is the case, only the "fragment" and "url" members will have
 * meaning, and the given URL structure may not be used as a base URL itself.
 */
enum UScheme
{
    USunknown,

    UShttp,
    UShttps,
    USftp,
    USfile,

    UScurrent,
};
@

<<[[Url]](webfs) per-scheme methods>>=
int         (*open)(Client*, Url*);
int         (*read)(Client*, Req*);
void        (*close)(Client*);
@


%claude:
The function pointers are what makes [[Url]] more than a record.
[[UShttp]] initializes them to [<httpopen()>], [<httpread()>], and [<httpclose()>],
[[USftp]] to the FTP equivalents, and so on.
%
Once an URL is parsed,
the [[webfs]] request loop never branches on [[ischeme]] again: it
just calls [[url->open(c, url)]] and lets C dispatch.

%claude:
The vtable lives inline in the [[Url]] itself, not as a separate
indirection:

\begin{verbatim}
    Url for "http://example.com/"           Url for "ftp://ftp.example.com/"
    ---------------------------------       ----------------------------------
    ischeme = UShttp                        ischeme = USftp
    open    = &httpopen     -----> code     open    = &ftpopen      -----> code
    read    = &httpread     -----> code     read    = &ftpread      -----> code
    close   = &httpclose    -----> code     close   = &ftpclose     -----> code
    host    = "example.com"                 host    = "ftp.example.com"
    path    = "/"                           path    = "/"
    ...                                     ...
\end{verbatim}

The cost is three extra pointers per [<Url>]; the win is that the
request loop in [[client.c]] is one polymorphic call and the next
scheme (e.g. \verb+gopher://+) is a matter of writing three
functions and one row in [<postparse>], with no edits to the
hot-path code.


%yoann: explain page_spec

<<[[Url]](webfs) union members>>=
struct {
    char *page_spec;
} http;
@


%claude:
Concretely, given the URL
\verb+https://alice@en.wikipedia.org:443/wiki/Cat?lang=en#refs+,
the [[Url]] struct is filled in like:

\begin{verbatim}
    url        = "https://alice@en.wikipedia.org:443/wiki/Cat?lang=en#refs"

    scheme     = "https"
    user       = "alice"
    passwd     = nil
    host       = "en.wikipedia.org"
    port       = "443"
    path       = "/wiki/Cat"
    query      = "lang=en"
    fragment   = "refs"

    ischeme    = UShttps
    open       = httpopen        \
    read       = httpread         > vtable bound to https
    close      = httpclose       /
    authority  = "alice@en.wikipedia.org:443"
    http.page_spec = "/wiki/Cat?lang=en"   (path + ? + query)
\end{verbatim}
%
The full URL string \verb+u->url+ is kept alongside the components as a
canonical serialization, maintained by [<rewriteurl()>] (covered later in
this section).


<<function [[freeurl]](webfs)>>=
void
freeurl(Url *u)
{
    if(u == nil)
        return;
    free(u->url);
    free(u->scheme);
    free(u->schemedata);
    free(u->authority);
    free(u->user);
    free(u->passwd);
    free(u->host);
    free(u->port);
    free(u->path);
    free(u->query);
    free(u->fragment);
    switch(u->ischeme){
    case UShttp:
        free(u->http.page_spec);
        break;
    <<[[freeurl()]] switch scheme other cases>>
    }
    free(u);
}
@

<<function [[copyurl]](webfs)>>=
Url*
copyurl(Url *u)
{
    Url *v;

    v = emalloc(sizeof(Url));
    *v = *u;
    dupp(&v->url);
    dupp(&v->scheme);
    dupp(&v->schemedata);
    dupp(&v->authority);
    dupp(&v->user);
    dupp(&v->passwd);
    dupp(&v->host);
    dupp(&v->port);
    dupp(&v->path);
    dupp(&v->query);
    dupp(&v->fragment);

    switch(v->ischeme){
    case UShttp:
        dupp(&v->http.page_spec);
        break;
    <<[[copyurl()]] switch scheme other cases>>
    }
    return v;
}
@


%XXX
<<[[Url]](webfs) other fields>>=
char*       schemedata;
char*       authority;
@


%claude:
[[rewriteurl()]] enforces an invariant: \verb+u->url+ is always the canonical
serialization of \verb+u+'s components. Whenever the request loop mutates a
field (e.g.\ following a redirect, or filling in a relative URL against a
base), it calls [[rewriteurl()]] to re-derive the string. That string is
what the kernel hands back when a client reads \verb+/mnt/web/N/parsed/url+.

<<function [[rewriteurl]](webfs)>>=
void
rewriteurl(Url *u)
{
    char *s;

    if(u->schemedata)
        s = estrmanydup(u->scheme, ":", u->schemedata, nil);
    else
        s = estrmanydup(u->scheme, "://", 
            u->user ? u->user : "",
            u->passwd ? ":" : "", u->passwd ? u->passwd : "",
            u->user ? "@" : "", u->host ? u->host : "", 
            u->port ? ":" : "", u->port ? u->port : "",
            u->path,
            u->query ? "?" : "", u->query ? u->query : "",
            u->fragment ? "#" : "", u->fragment ? u->fragment : "",
            nil);
    free(u->url);
    u->url = s;
}
@




\subsection{[[SplitUrl]]}

%claude:
[[SplitUrl]] is the parser's intermediate form: pairs of pointers into the
input string, one per RFC 3986 component. No allocation happens during
parsing; only after the components are validated does \verb+url.c+ copy them
into the heap-allocated [<Url>].

<<struct [[SplitUrl]](webfs)>>=
struct SplitUrl
{
    struct {
        char *s;
        char *e;
    } url, scheme, authority, path, query, fragment;
};
@

For our example URL above, the [[SplitUrl]] looks like:

\begin{verbatim}
    input string:   "https://alice@en.wikipedia.org:443/wiki/Cat?lang=en#refs"
                     ^   ^^ ^                       ^^         ^^      ^^   ^
                     |    \  \______ authority _____/ \__ path _/  \query/ \frag/
                     |     +- (skip ":")
                     +- scheme

    SplitUrl:
        url       = (s -> "https...", e -> end)
        scheme    = (s -> "https",    e -> "h"+5)
        authority = (s -> "alice@...", e -> "/wiki/Cat...")
        path      = (s -> "/wiki/Cat", e -> "?lang=en...")
        query     = (s -> "lang=en",   e -> "#refs")
        fragment  = (s -> "refs",      e -> end)
\end{verbatim}

Each (s, e) pair is a half-open slice into the original input.
The next phase ([<parse_scheme()>], [<parse_authority()>], etc.)
validates each slice and only then [[estredup]]s it into the
[[Url]] struct's heap-allocated fields.



<<function [[dupp]](webfs)>>=
static void
dupp(char **p)
{
    if(*p)
        *p = estrdup(*p);
}
@


%XXX
<<function [[seturlquery]](webfs)>>=
int
seturlquery(Url *u, char *query)
{
    if(query == nil){
        free(u->query);
        u->query = nil;
        return 0;
    }

    if(!ismatch(REquery, query, "query"))
        return -1;

    free(u->query);
    u->query = estrdup(query);
    return 0;
}
@

