\section{The [[/mnt/web]] interface}

%claude:
The shape of [[webfs]]'s file tree is the entire public API of the
network side of the browser. A client process opens \verb+/mnt/web/clone+,
reads back a connection number~\verb+N+, then writes \verb+get http://...+
to \verb+/mnt/web/N/ctl+ and reads bytes from \verb+/mnt/web/N/body+. There
is no library in between; the semantics are spelled out in the kernel
namespace, not in a header file.

%claude:
Concretely, fetching \verb+http://example.com/+ from a shell session
goes like:

\begin{verbatim}
    % cat /mnt/web/clone                    # open + read returns the conn number
    7
    % echo url http://example.com/ > /mnt/web/7/ctl
    % cat /mnt/web/7/contenttype
    text/html
    % cat /mnt/web/7/parsed/host
    example.com
    % cat /mnt/web/7/body
    <!doctype html><html>...</html>
\end{verbatim}

Every line here is a normal file operation: nothing in this session
required linking a library. The same sequence inside [[mothra]]
([[webclone]] in [[mothra/url.c]]) is ten lines of C calling
[[open]], [[read]], [[write]], and a few [[snprint]]s.

%claude:
The chunk below which is the comment at the top of \verb+webfs/fs.c+ describes
that tree. I reproduce it verbatim because the comment is itself the
specification:

<<webfs/fs.c toplevel comment>>=
/*
 * Web file system.  Conventionally mounted at /mnt/web
 *
 *      ctl                             send control messages (might go away)
 *      cookies                 list of cookies, editable
 *      clone                   open and read to obtain new connection
 *      n                               connection directory
 *              ctl                             control messages (like get url)
 *              body                            retrieved data
 *              content-type            mime content-type of body
 *              postbody                        data to be posted
 *              parsed                  parsed version of url
 *                      url                             entire url
 *                      scheme                  http, ftp, etc.
 *                      host                            hostname
 *                      path                            path on host
 *                      query                   query after path
 *                      fragment                        #foo anchor reference
 *                      user                            user name (ftp)
 *                      password                        password (ftp)
 *                      ftptype                 transfer mode (ftp)
 */
@

\subsection{[[Qxxx]]}

%claude:
Every entry in the previous tree corresponds to one of the \verb+Qxxx+
constants below. [[webfs]]'s 9P implementation uses the value of
\verb+(Qid).path+ to remember which file a fid points at; this enum is the
encoding. \verb+Qclone+ and \verb+Qcookies+ live at the root, while everything
from \verb+Qctl+ onwards lives inside a per-connection directory whose own
\verb+Qid.path+ folds in the connection number.

<<enum Qxxx(webfs)>>=
enum
{
    // '/'
    Qroot,

    // toplevel entries
    Qrootctl,
    Qcookies,
    Qclone,

    // ??
    Qclient,

    // the /n/xxx entries
    Qctl,
    Qbody,
    Qcontenttype,
    Qpostbody,
    Qparsed,

    // ??
    Qbodyext,

    // parsed url components
    Qurl,
    Qscheme,
    Quser,
    Qpasswd,
    Qhost,
    Qport,
    Qpath,
    Qquery,
    Qfragment,

    // ??
    Qschemedata,

    <<[[Qxxx]] other cases>>

    Qend,
};
@

\subsection{[[Tab]]}

%claude:
[[Tab]] is the static table mapping each \verb+Qxxx+ to its name and Unix
permission bits. Walk requests look up an entry by name; \verb+stat+ requests
look it up by \verb+offset+ (which equals the \verb+Qxxx+ value).

<<struct [[Tab]](webfs)>>=
