\subsection{[[Cookie]]}

%claude:
A [[Cookie]] in [[webfs]] carries everything Set-Cookie spelled out
(name, value, domain, path, expires, secure).

<<struct [[Cookie]](webfs)>>=
struct Cookie
{
    /* external info */
    char*       name;
    char*       value;
    char*       dom;            /* starts with . */
    char*       path;
    uint        expire;         /* time of expiration: ~0 means when webcookies dies */
    bool        secure;

    <<[[Cookie]](webfs) other fields>>
};
@


<<[[Cookie]](webfs) other fields>>=
bool         explicitdom;    /* dom was explicitly set */
bool         explicitpath;   /* path was explicitly set */
@

%plus three book-keeping
%fields. \verb+netscapestyle+ remembers whether the original header used the
%Netscape format (no \verb+Version+ attribute, slightly different domain
%matching) so that the cookie is sent back in the same shape it was given.
%\verb+explicitdom+ and \verb+explicitpath+ remember whether the server set
%those fields itself or whether [[webfs]] defaulted them from the request
%URL --- the spec says the two cases match differently. \verb+ondisk+ flags
%cookies already persisted to \verb+/usr/web/cookies+; the in-memory jar can
%then be repacked without rewriting unchanged entries.


%XXX
<<[[Cookie]](webfs) other fields>>=
char*       version;
char*       comment;                /* optional, may be nil */

int         netscapestyle;

/* internal info */
int         deleted;
int         mark;
bool         ondisk;
@



%claude:
A real cookie filled in from a wire \verb+Set-Cookie:+ header.
Wire form:

\begin{verbatim}
    Set-Cookie: sess=abc123; Domain=.example.com; Path=/; Expires=Sun, 06-Nov-2026 08:49:37 GMT; Secure
\end{verbatim}

\noindent As parsed into a [<Cookie>] struct:

\begin{verbatim}
    name           = "sess"
    value          = "abc123"
    dom            = ".example.com"      <- leading dot: matches subdomains
    path           = "/"
    expire         = 1762416577          <- Unix time of "06-Nov-2026 08:49:37 GMT"
    secure         = 1                   <- only sent over https://

    explicitdom    = 1                   <- server set Domain= explicitly
    explicitpath   = 1                   <- server set Path= explicitly
    netscapestyle  = 1                   <- no Version attr in source
    ondisk         = 0                   <- not yet flushed to /usr/web/cookies
\end{verbatim}

A subsequent request to \verb+https://www.example.com/anything+
would match this cookie (the request host \verb+www.example.com+ ends
in \verb+.example.com+, the request path \verb+/anything+ starts with
\verb+/+, the scheme is HTTPS so the secure flag is satisfied) and
echo it back as \verb+Cookie: sess=abc123+.



\subsection{[[Jar]]}

%claude:
The [[Jar]] is a flat append-only [<Cookie>] array (\verb+nc+ filled out of
\verb+mc+ allocated). 

<<struct [[Jar]](webfs)>>=
struct Jar
{
    // array<ref_own<Cookie>>, len = nc, allocated = mc
    Cookie      *c;
    int         nc;
    int         mc;

    <<[[Jar]](webfs) other fields>>
};
@

%XXX
<<[[Jar]](webfs) other fields>>=
Qid         qid;
int         dirty;
char                *file;
char                *lockfile;
@
%claude:
The \verb+qid+ and \verb+dirty+ fields support the
multi-process lock-file protocol: if a second [[webfs]] instance has
modified \verb+/usr/web/cookies+ on disk (its qid changed), the in-memory
jar is reread before any cookie operation is allowed to commit.


