\section{HTML parse tree (mothra's flat item list)}

%claude:
Mothra does not build a DOM. Instead, the parser walks the input HTML once
and produces a flat list of \verb+Rtext+ nodes (defined in \verb+libpanel+,
not here): one per text run or per atomic widget like an image or form
field. ``Tag dispatch'' just means: when the lexer recognizes
\verb+<b>+ it switches the current font, when it recognizes \verb+</b>+ it
switches back, when it recognizes \verb+<img>+ it appends one
[[Rtext]]+[<Action>] pair, and so on. The tree the W3C calls a DOM never
exists; what reaches the layout engine is the same kind of stream a text
editor would use to display a styled document.

%claude:
The next four chunks are the alphabet of that scheme: token names
([<Tagxxx>]), their text-to-id table ([<Tag>]), token types ([<Txx>]), and
the per-tag side-data attached to special items ([<Action>], [<Pair>]).

%claude:
Concretely, the input fragment
\verb+Click <a href="X">here</a> for X+ becomes three [[Rtext]] nodes:

\begin{verbatim}
    Rtext       text         font   action                  flags
    -------------------------------------------------------------
    [0]         "Click "     ROMAN  -                       -
    [1]         "here"       ROMAN  Action{                 PL_HOT
                                      link  = "X",
                                      name  = nil,
                                      image = nil,
                                      ...
                                    }
    [2]         " for X"     ROMAN  -                       -
\end{verbatim}

The \verb+<a>+ open tag did not produce a node; it pushed a frame
onto the parser's formatting stack with \verb+state->link = "X"+. The
text run inside captured that frame into its [<Action>], and the
[[PL_HOT]] flag tells [[libpanel]] to render it as a clickable link.
The \verb+</a>+ close tag popped the frame, which is why
\verb+" for X"+ has no [<Action>].

