[[Entity]] is one row of the named-character-reference table that turns
\verb+&amp;+ into U+0026, \verb+&lambda;+ into U+03BB, and so on. The full
table is one of the larger source files in mothra; lookup is a simple linear
scan because it only happens during parsing.

<<struct [[Entity]](mothra)>>=
struct Entity{
    char *name;
    Rune value;
};
@

\section{Mothra's view (text runs, layout, panels)}


\subsection{[[Www]]}

%claude:
[[Www]] is one open page in mothra: its URL, its parsed text (the linked
list of \verb+Rtext+ nodes the layout panel actually walks), its title,
and side caches for inline images (\verb+pix+) and form state
(\verb+form+).


<<struct [[Www]](mothra)>>=
struct Www{

    //ref_own<Url>
    Url *url;
    // list<Rtext>, next= ?
    Rtext *text;
    char title[NTITLE];

    // list<Pix>, next = Pix.next, image cache
    void *pix;
    // form state, type=??
    void *form;

    bool changed;               /* reader sets this every time it updates page */
    int finished;               /* reader sets this when done */
    int alldone;                /* page will not change further -- used to adjust cursor */

    <<[[Www]] other fields>>
};
@

%claude:
The three flags at the bottom of [[Www]] are the protocol between the
reader thread and the redrawing thread: \verb+changed+ says a redraw is
due, \verb+finished+ says the body is fully read, \verb+alldone+ says even
the deferred image fetches have settled (so the busy cursor can finally
go away).

%XXX
<<[[Www]] other fields>>=
int yoffs;
int gottitle;               /* title got drawn */
@


\subsection{[[Pix]]}

%claude:
[<Pix>] is one decoded image, identified by URL and target
width/height. \verb+w->pix+ is a linked list of all images for the
current page, used to deduplicate when the same image appears multiple
times (e.g.\ icon strips).

<<struct [[Pix]](mothra)>>=
struct Pix{
    Image *b;

    int width;
    int height;

    char name[NNAME];

    // list<Pix>, head = Www.pix
    Pix *next;
};
@


%\subsection{Summary}

%claude:
The graph of relationships between [<Www>], [[Rtext]], [<Action>],
and [<Pix>] for one rendered page:

\begin{verbatim}
        Www                           Pix                Pix
        ---                           ---                ---
        url ---> Url                  next -----------> next ---> nil
        text                          b (Image*)        b (Image*)
        |                             ^
        |                             |
        v                             |
       Rtext --> Rtext --> Rtext --> Rtext --> Rtext --> ...   (linked list)
        text     text       text      text     text
        font     font       font      font     font
        flags    flags      flags     flags    flags
        user                user
         |                   |
         v                   v
        Action              Action
        link="/foo"         image="logo.png"
        name=nil            link=nil
                            ...        \________________ once decoded ___> Pix.b
\end{verbatim}

The \verb+Rtext+ list is the only path from [<Www>] to the visible
content. Everything else hangs off it: per-node [<Action>] for links
and image refs, and the [<Pix>] cache holding the decoded bitmaps that
\verb+Rtext+ entries point back into via their \verb+b+ field once
[[getpix]] finishes.


