%******************************************************************************
\chapter{[[mothra]]: [[main()]] and Panels}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:mothra-main}

%claude:
This chapter introduces the program at the centre of the book: the
\verb+mothra+ binary. It is what the user actually launches; everything
else in the book is invoked behind the scenes by mothra ([[webfs]]
already mounted as a service, image format converters spawned per image,
etc.).
%toc:
I cover five pieces here in order:
the [[main()]] skeleton,
the arguments mothra accepts,
the static layout of its window (a four-pane stack of \verb+libpanel+ panels),
the main I/O loop that runs as long as the browser is open, and
the worker procedure that streams a URL's body into a [<Www>].

\section{[[main()]] skeleton}


%claude:
Most of the architectural weight of mothra is in [<main()>].
Read in one sitting it looks unremarkable --- argument parsing, draw/initdraw,
an event loop --- but if you take it apart clause by
clause, every Plan~9 subsystem the browser uses appears at least once:
\verb+initdraw+ (see \book{Graphics}) and
\verb+plinit+ (see \book{Widgets}) for graphics,
\verb+einit+ (and \verb+eplumb+) for the event multiplexer (see \book{Graphics}),
\verb+rfork+ for the cohort group,
a self-pipe \verb+kickpipe+ for waking the loop from worker threads, and the
plumb-message intake that lets external programs send a URL with one
\verb+plumb+ command. 


<<global [[mothra]](mothra)>>=
char mothra[] = "mothra!";
@

<<function [[main]](mothra)>>=
void main(int argc, char *argv[]){
    char *url;
    int i;
    Event e;
    <<[[main()]](mothra) other locals>>

    <<[[main()]](mothra) fmt setup>>
    ARGBEGIN{
    <<[[main()]](mothra) command line processing part 1>>
    default:  goto Usage;
    }ARGEND

    <<[[main()]](mothra) cohort setup>>

    // command line processing part 2
    switch(argc){
    case 1: 
        url=argv[0];
        break;
    <<[[main()]](mothra) switch [[argc]] other cases>>
    default:
    Usage:
        fprint(STDERR, "usage: %s [-dvak] [-m mtpt] [url]\n", argv0);
        exits("usage");
    }

    if(initdraw(0, 0, mothra) < 0)
        sysfatal("initdraw: %r");
    <<[[main()]](mothra) extra draw settings>>

    einit(Emouse|Ekeyboard);

    <<[[main()]](mothra) plumb initialisation>>
    <<[[main()]](mothra) kickpipe initialisation>>

    plinit(view->depth);

    <<[[main()]](mothra) debug notify>>

    <<[[main()]](mothra) graphics initialisation>>

    mkpanels();

    unlockdisplay(display);

    eresized(false);
    drawlock(1);

    if(url && url[0])
        geturl(url, -1, 1, 0);

    mouse.buttons=0;
    for(;;){
          <<[[main()]](mothra) in event loop, if [[current]] and no buttons>>
          
          drawlock(0);
          i=event(&e);
          drawlock(1);
          
          switch(i){
          <<[[main()]](mothra) in event loop, switch [[i]] cases>>
          }
    }
}
@

%claude:
\verb+initdraw()+ sets up \verb+libdraw+, \verb+plinit()+ sets
up \verb+libpanel+, \verb+einit()+ wires mouse and keyboard into the
\verb+event(2)+ multiplexer.
[<mkpanels()>] builds the visible four-pane layout and
[<geturl()>] kicks off the initial fetch.

%claude:
The loop itself will dispatch between five event sources: \verb+Ekick+
(redraw the current page), \verb+Ekeyboard+ (scrolling and search),
\verb+Emouse+ (clicks, side-scrolls via buttons~4 and~5), \verb+Eplumb+
(an external URL request), and the implicit ``current page just finished
loading'' branch at the top of the loop, which scrolls to the
\verb+#fragment+ if any and resets the busy cursor.

%yoann: explain

