\section{The dual cookie architecture: [[webfs/cookies.c]] vs standalone [[webcookies]]}

%claude:
There are two cookie implementations in the browser: one inside webfs
(\verb+webfs/cookies.c+, used when nothing is mounted at
\verb+/mnt/webcookies+), one standalone (\verb+webcookies+, used when it
is). The standalone version is what allows multiple webfs instances to
share a single cookie jar; the inline one is the no-dependency default
that lets webfs work on its own. Both share the same on-disk format, the
same struct layout, and most of the parsing code by physical copy. The
duplication is the cost of having webfs work without dragging in another
file server, set against the benefit of having a real shared jar when
the user wants one.


