\section{Why split from [[webfs]]}

%claude:
The split is for the same reason that webfs is its own process. Cookies
are user-session state, not per-process state. If webfs owned cookies
exclusively, then two webfs processes (one per browser window, say) could
not share a login session for example.com, which is exactly the
behaviour users expect from a browser. By promoting cookies to a
file-server protocol, any number of cookie clients can share one jar.
The price is one more 9P round-trip per request, which is invisible
under network latency.

