\section{[[uhtml]]: sniffing and shelling out}

%claude:
\verb+uhtml+ is the dispatcher in front of \verb+tcs+. It buffers the
first 64~KiB of its input, sniffs the encoding from the bytes (BOMs at
the start of the buffer, then \verb+<meta charset="...">+ and
\verb+<?xml encoding="...">+ in the head), then either passes through if
the data is already UTF-8 or execs
\verb+rc -c "tcs -f <cset> | tcs -f html"+ as the rest of its tail. The two-stage tcs pipeline first
converts to UTF-8 and then to ``html'' (which decodes named entities
like \verb+&lambda;+ into runes), so by the time the bytes reach
mothra's parser they are clean Plan~9 UTF-8.

<<constant [[IOUNIT]](uhtml)>>=
#define IOUNIT (64*1024)
@

<<function [[usage]](uhtml)>>=
void
usage(void)
{
    fprint(2, "%s [ -p ] [ -c charset ] [ file ]\n", argv0);
    exits("usage");
}
@

<<function [[attr]](uhtml)>>=
char*
attr(char *s, char *a)
{
    char *e, q;

    if((s = cistrstr(s, a)) == nil)
        return nil;
    s += strlen(a);
    while(*s && strchr(whitespace, *s))
        s++;
    if(*s++ != '=')
        return nil;
    while(*s && strchr(whitespace, *s))
        s++;
    q = 0;
    if(*s == '"' || *s == '\'')
        q = *s++;
    for(e = s; *e; e++){
        if(*e == q)
            break;
        if(isalnum(*e))
            continue;
        if(*e == '-' || *e == '_')
            continue;
        break;
    }
    if((e - s) > 1)
        return smprint("%.*s", (int)(e - s), s);
    return nil;
}
@

<<function [[main]](uhtml)>>=
void
main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    int n, q, pfd[2], pflag = 0;
    char *arg[4], *s, *g, *e, *p, *a, t;
    Rune r;

    ARGBEGIN {
    case 'c':
        cset = EARGF(usage());
        break;
    case 'p':
        pflag = 1;
        break;
    default:
        usage();
    } ARGEND;
    if(*argv){
        close(0);
        if(open(*argv, OREAD) != 0)
            sysfatal("open: %r");
    }
    nbuf = 0;
    while(nbuf < sizeof(buf)-1){
        if((n = read(0, buf + nbuf, sizeof(buf)-1-nbuf)) <= 0)
            break;
        nbuf += n;
        buf[nbuf] = 0;
    }

    p = buf;
    if(nbuf >= 3 && memcmp(p, "\xEF\xBB\xBF", 3)==0){
        p += 3;
        nbuf -= 3;
        cset = "utf";
        goto Found;
    }
    if(nbuf >= 2 && memcmp(p, "\xFE\xFF", 2) == 0){
        p += 2;
        nbuf -= 2;
        cset = "unicode-be";
        goto Found;
    }
    if(nbuf >= 2 && memcmp(p, "\xFF\xFE", 2) == 0){
        p += 2;
        nbuf -= 2;
        cset = "unicode-le";
        goto Found;
    }

    s = p;
    do {
        if((s = strchr(s, '<')) == nil)
            break;
        q = 0;
        g = ++s;
        e = buf+nbuf;
        while(s < e){
            if(*s == '=' && q == 0)
                q = '=';
            else if(*s == '\'' || *s == '"'){
                if(q == '=')
                    q = *s;
                else if(q == *s)
                    q = 0;
            }
            else if(*s == '>' && q != '\'' && q != '"'){
                e = s;
                break;
            }
            else if(q == '=' && strchr(whitespace, *s) == nil)
                q = 0;
            s++;
        }
        t = *e;
        *e = 0;
        if((a = attr(g, "encoding")) != nil || (a = attr(g, "charset")) != nil)
        if(cistrcmp(a, "utf") != 0 && cistrcmp(a, "utf-8") != 0){
            cset = a;
            *e = t;
            break;
        }
        *e = t;
        s = ++e;
    } while(t);

    s = p;
    while(s+UTFmax < p+nbuf){
        s += chartorune(&r, s);
        if(r == Runeerror){
            if(cset == nil)
                cset = "latin1";
            goto Found;
        }
    }
    cset = "utf";

Found:
    if(pflag){
        print("%s\n", cset);
        exits(0);
    }

    if(nbuf == 0){
        write(1, p, 0);
        exits(0);
    }

    if(pipe(pfd) < 0)
        sysfatal("pipe: %r");

    switch(rfork(RFFDG|RFREND|RFPROC)){
    case -1:
        sysfatal("fork: %r");
    case 0:
        dup(pfd[0], 0);
        close(pfd[0]);
        close(pfd[1]);

        arg[0] = "rc";
        arg[1] = "-c";
        arg[2] = smprint("{tcs -f %s || cat} | tcs -f html", cset);
        arg[3] = nil;
        exec("/bin/rc", arg);
    }

    dup(pfd[1], 1);
    close(pfd[0]);
    close(pfd[1]);

    while(nbuf > 0){
        if(write(1, p, nbuf) != nbuf)
            sysfatal("write: %r");
        p = buf;
        if((nbuf = read(0, p, sizeof(buf)-1)) < 0)
            sysfatal("read: %r");
    }
    close(1);
    waitpid();
    exits(0);
}
@

\section{The full pipeline: [[fetch | uhtml | render]]}

%claude:
Putting it all together: when mothra fetches an HTML page, the bytes
flow through three subprocesses joined by pipes.

\begin{verbatim}
    /mnt/web/N/body          uhtml                tcs                    mothra
    (raw bytes from         (sniff cs,          (Latin-1 -> UTF-8,      (parse, render)
     webfs+http+tls)         pass thru                or pass thru
                             or fork tcs)            via two stages)

    \-----------------------/  \---------------------/  \------/
            pipe 1                      pipe 2          pipe 3
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
Mothra creates pipe~1 in [<urlget()>] (\verb+webclone+ + open of
\verb+/body+), then [<geturl()>] sees \verb+typ == HTML+ and stitches
\verb+uhtml+ onto the front via [<pipeline()>]. \verb+uhtml+ in turn may
exec \verb+tcs+ on its tail. Mothra ends up reading clean UTF-8 from a
fd whose far end is webfs's HTTP body, with two filters in between, none
of which mothra had to link.

%###############################################################################
\part{Rendering the Page}
%###############################################################################

%claude:
With clean UTF-8 in hand, this part turns bytes into pixels. HTML
parsing ([[rdhtml.c]]) is the central machinery: a single-pass
tokenizer that emits a flat list of [<Rtext>] nodes---no DOM, no AST,
no separate stylesheet pass. Content dispatch picks which parser to
run based on the MIME type the server returned (plain text, HTML, an
image type, a download). Layout walks the [<Rtext>] list to wrap text
and place inline images and form widgets; the tag-by-tag rendering,
table, image, and form chapters each cover one slice of that walk.
All of them feed the same [<Rtext>] list and the same libpanel layout
engine described in \book{Widgets}.

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{HTML Parsing: [[rdhtml.c]]}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:html-parsing}

%claude:
\verb+rdhtml.c+ is the single biggest file in mothra. It is the HTML
parser: a hand-written single-pass tokenizer + state machine that turns
the byte stream of a \verb+<html>...</html>+ document into a flat list of
\verb+Rtext+ nodes. ``Flat list, not DOM'' is the part to keep in mind.
Most modern browsers build a tree of HTML elements first and lay it out
second, partly because CSS and JavaScript want to query and mutate the
tree. Mothra has no CSS or JavaScript and renders top-to-bottom in one
pass, so the parser emits visual items directly. There is no
intermediate AST.

%claude:
The flow is: an outer loop pulls one token (TAG, ENDTAG, or TEXT) from
the byte stream; a switch dispatches on the token; for TAGs, a second
switch dispatches on which tag (\verb+<b>+, \verb+<a href=...>+,
\verb+<img>+, \ldots) and updates the formatting state on a small parse
stack; for TEXTs, the current formatting state is captured into a fresh
\verb+Rtext+ node and appended to the output. Two runtime-allocated
buffers ([[token]], [[hbuf]]) and a fixed-size formatting stack are all
the parser needs.

\section{What mothra parses (HTML4-ish, lenient)}

%claude:
The parser is HTML4-ish in scope and lenient in posture: every tag has
to be recognized, every tag attribute parsed, but nothing has to be
syntactically correct. Real-world HTML is full of unclosed tags,
mismatched closes, and missing attribute quotes; the parser tolerates
all of them by treating the tag dispatch as advisory updates to the
formatting stack rather than as hierarchy assertions.

%claude:
The state for a parser is bundled into one struct, [<Hglob>], that
threads through every helper. This is so that two parsers can run in
parallel without clobbering each other: mothra forks one parser per
inflight page (a navigation while another page is still loading kicks
off two simultaneous parses). \verb+Hglob+ is the per-parse context;
[<Stack>] is one element of the formatting parse stack inside it.

<<struct [[Hglob]](mothra)>>=
/*
 * Globals -- these are packed up into a struct that gets passed around
 * so that multiple parsers can run concurrently
 */
struct Hglob{
    char *tp;           /* pointer in text buffer */
    char *name;         /* input file name */
    int hfd;            /* input file descriptor */
    char hbuf[NHBUF];   /* input buffer */
    char *hbufp;                /* next character in buffer */
    char *ehbuf;                /* end of good characters in buffer */
    int heof;           /* end of file flag */
    int peekc[NPEEKC];  /* characters to re-read */
    int npeekc;         /* # of characters to re-read */
    char token[NTOKEN]; /* if token type is TEXT */
    Pair attr[NATTR];   /* tag attribute/value pairs */
    int nsp;            /* # of white-space characters before TEXT token */
    int spacc;          /* place to accumulate more spaces */
                /* if negative, won't accumulate! */
    int tag;            /* if token type is TAG or END */

    Stack stack[NSTACK];        /* parse stack */
    Stack *state;               /* parse stack pointer */

    int lineno;         /* input line number */
    int linebrk;                /* flag set if we require a line-break in output */
    int para;           /* flag set if we need an indent at the break */
    char *text;         /* text buffer */
    char *etext;                /* end of text buffer */
    Form *form;         /* data for form under construction */

    Www *dst;           /* where the text goes */
};
@

%claude:
[<Stack>] is one frame of the parser's formatting stack. When the parser
sees \verb+<b>+ it pushes a new frame whose \verb+font+ field is BOLD;
when it sees \verb+</b>+ it pops. Same idea for \verb+<i>+,
\verb+<pre>+, \verb+<sub>+, \verb+<a href=...>+, \verb+<img>+, list
indentation. Every TEXT token captured inherits the top-of-stack
formatting --- so HTML's nested-tag semantics are reduced to a stack of
mutable formatting records, with the visible text taking a snapshot.

<<struct [[Stack]](mothra)>>=
struct Stack{
    int tag;            /* html tag being processed */
    int pre;            /* in preformatted text? */
    int font;           /* typeface */
    int size;           /* point size of text */
    int sub;            /* < 0 superscript, > 0 subscript */
    int margin;         /* left margin position */
    int indent;         /* extra indent at paragraph start */
    int number;         /* paragraph number */
    int ismap;          /* flag of <img> */
    int isscript;               /* inside <script> */
    int strike;         /* flag of <strike> */
    int width;          /* size of image */
    int height;

    char *image;                /* arg of <img> */
    char *link;         /* arg of <a href=...> */
    char *name;         /* arg of <a name=...> */
};
@

<<constant [[NSTACK]](mothra)>>=
#define NSTACK  100     /* html grammar is not recursive, so 30 or so should do */
@

<<constant [[NHBUF]](mothra)>>=
#define NHBUF   8192 //IOUNIT   /* Input buffer size */
@

<<constant [[NPEEKC]](mothra)>>=
#define NPEEKC  3       /* Maximum lookahead */
@

<<constant [[NTOKEN]](mothra)>>=
#define NTOKEN  65536   /* Maximum token length */
@

<<constant [[NATTR]](mothra)>>=
#define NATTR   512     /* Maximum number of attributes of a tag */
@

<<constant [[STAG]](mothra)>>=
/*
 * Magic characters corresponding to
 *      literal < followed by / ! or alpha,
 *      literal > and
 *      end of file
 */
#define STAG    65536
@

<<constant [[ETAG]](mothra)>>=
#define ETAG    65537
@

<<constant [[EOF]](mothra)>>=
#define EOF     -1
@

\section{Tokenization: tags, attributes, text runs}

%claude:
The tokenizer reads bytes one rune at a time, classifies each into a
TAG, ENDTAG, or TEXT token, and stuffs the result into the \verb+Hglob+
slots [[token]] (for TEXT runs) or [[attr]] (for parsed
attribute/value pairs of a tag). The peeking primitives push runes back
into the input via [<Hglob>]'s \verb+peekc+ array. Three special
sentinels mark uncommon byte values: \verb+STAG+ = found \verb+<+ that
starts a tag, \verb+ETAG+ = found \verb+>+ that closes one, \verb+EOF+ =
end of input. Sticking these out-of-band values into a \verb+int+
return type keeps the lexer's caller from confusing them with real
runes.

